<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> The alliance includes opportunistic forbs of alkaline marshes. <i>Anemopsis californica </i>is a common marsh plant that is tolerant of alkaline or saline, clay soils. This herbaceous perennial has a woody rootstock and aromatic rhizomes. The flowers lack a perianth and form a conical-shaped head subtended by 4-8 unequal, white, petal-like bracts. The waxy, dull, gray-green leaves have a spicy smell. Many tribes in California and the Southwest used the root of the plant as a medicine (Anderson and Roderick 2000). <br/>
<br/>
Similarly, <i>Solidago confinis </i>and <i>S. spectabilis </i>are tolerant of clay soils, alkalinity and salinity, and seasonal flooding. Plants have plumes of small, yellow flowers, which attract bees, butterflies, and other pollinators (Calflora 2018).<br/>
<br/>
Stands of <i>A. californica </i>are typically small and occur in isolated inland wetlands and riparian zones. In California, it associates with <i>Platanus racemosa, Populus fremontii, Salix </i>spp., and riparian herbs. Elsewhere, <i>A. californica </i>is an understory plant of <i>Populus deltoides </i>stands in New Mexico (NatureServe 2007a). Most stands occur in a fine-scale matrix and need to be sampled individually.<br/>
<br/>
This alliance has been expanded to include additional species since the 2009 publication of  <i>A Manual of California Vegetation, second edition</i>.  In southeastern California stands of  <i>Solidago spectabilis</i> and  <i>Helianthus nuttallii</i> occur in a matrix with various herbs, sometimes including <i>Anemopsis californica</i>. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
