    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa, Ac, Ak-l). Stands have been observed in marshes and sloughs in Contra Costa Co. and along streams in Alameda Co. In San Luis Obispo Co., stands may be found near the coast in sand dunes and along river edges (Calflora 2018, Calphotos 2018).</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Aa, Ac-d, Aj). Stands have been observed in the section, including along the Cuyama River in San Luis Obispo Co. (Calflora 2018).</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aj-k, Aq, Au, Ay-z). A meadow stand of <i>Anemopsis californica</i> occurs in a floodplain of Grapevine Creek (Moe 2004). Additional stands were sampled in the southeast and southwest portions of the ecoregion section (Buck-Diaz et al. 2012). Stands have been observed along sloughs in Solano Co. and Conta Costa Co. (Calflora 2018).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa-b, Ae, Ag-j, An). Small stands occur in alkali wetlands adjacent to stands of <i>Juncus cooperi, Schoenoplectus americanus,</i> and other wetland alliances at Zzyzx Hot Springs.  Stands also occur at springs in Death Valley National Park (Evens et al. 2014). Stands have been observed throughout the Owens Valley and Rose Valley at alkali wet meadows along the valley floor and at streams crossing fans below the Sierra Nevada. Outside of Mono Co. and Inyo Co., the alliance is restricted to isolated springs and seeps, moist playas, and along rivers. <i>Solidago confinis</i> or <i>S. spectabilis</i> occupy more montane sites.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dh-i). Stands occur in the upper Owens River Valley near Bishop at Fish Slough (Odion et al. 1992a, VegCAMP 2014b). Stands have been observed near Mono Lake.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Er, Eu). Stands of <i>A. californica</i> have been observed in wet places on the Kern Plateau and grassy wet areas and alkaline seeps along the eastern slope. <i>Solidago confinis</i> has also been observed at springs along the eastern slope (Consortium of California Herbaria 2018; Calflora 2018).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fc-e). Stands have been sampled along the historic floodplain of the Kern River below Isabella Reservoir (CNPS 2008).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fd-f). A stand was sampled in the Grapevine Mountains of Death Valley National Park (Evens et al. 2014). Isolated stands have been observed at springs in the Panamint Mountains and the Coso Range.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-b, Bd, Bg, Bi-j). At least one stand lies between a freshwater seep and a salt marsh in the Ballona Wetlands Wildlife Area, Los Angeles Co. (CNDDB 2008). Stands have been observed at marshes adjacent to coastal lagoons in San Diego Co. and Santa Barbara Co. and along the edge of springs in Santa Barabara Co. (Consortium of California Herbaria 2018; Calflora 2018).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-l, Bn-p). Stands occur in saturated wetlands in the Lake Hodges area east to San Felipe Valley in San Diego Co. (Evens and San 2005) and in the Santa Ana Mountains in western Riverside Co. (Klein and Evens 2005). Stands can be found in areas of wet soil and alkaline flats and seeps in valleys throughout this section (Consortium of California Herbaria 2018; Calflora 2018).
Stands of <i>Solidago confinis</i>  have been observed in saline wetlands, meadows, and wet areas along rivers and creeks in the mountain ranges throughout this section (Consortium of California Herbaria 2018; Calflora 2018).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Db-c). Stands have been observed in seasonally wet grasslands and meadows in Siskiyou Co. (CCH 2018, Calphotos 2018).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Ranchers consider <i>Anemopsis californica</i>  invasive in pastures. It is unpalatable to livestock and increases with grazing. <i>Solidago </i>spp., on the other hand, have fair to good palatability for livestock. Taxa in this alliance were used by Native American tribes for various medicinal uses. Due to the rhizomatous nature of <i>Anemopsis californica </i>and <i>Solidago </i>spp., they can be used for revegetation of disturbed areas and for soil stabilization (Anderson and Roderick 2000, Pavek 2011). </div>
</div>

    

    

